	<item>
		<title>By: Keith Wallace</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/bass-tips/how-to-record-your-bass.html#comment-17171</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Keith Wallace]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 02 Jun 2016 23:09:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=11715#comment-17171</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Hi Jonathan. You&#039;d need a DI box if the final thing in your chain is expecting a microphone level input, like a mixing desk. Or only has a 3 pin XLR input socket. Or if your bass signal is too hot (level too high) and you are getting distortion when you record. Or finally, if you have a really really long cable run and you are getting interference.

In your case none of these things should apply, so no you don&#039;t need a DI box. The Scarlett 2i2 is designed to take in an input at Line Level, which is what your amp is putting out. If you are getting distortion, you can turn down the gain dial until it&#039;s green, or change between the Instrument and Mic switch.

Hope you&#039;re still playing 9 months on!]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Hi Jonathan. You&#8217;d need a DI box if the final thing in your chain is expecting a microphone level input, like a mixing desk. Or only has a 3 pin XLR input socket. Or if your bass signal is too hot (level too high) and you are getting distortion when you record. Or finally, if you have a really really long cable run and you are getting interference.</p>
<p>In your case none of these things should apply, so no you don&#8217;t need a DI box. The Scarlett 2i2 is designed to take in an input at Line Level, which is what your amp is putting out. If you are getting distortion, you can turn down the gain dial until it&#8217;s green, or change between the Instrument and Mic switch.</p>
<p>Hope you&#8217;re still playing 9 months on!</p>
]]></content:encoded>
