		<title>By: Christopher Michael Willett</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/bass-tips/how-to-record-your-bass.html#comment-17166</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Christopher Michael Willett]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 02 Jun 2016 17:15:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=11715#comment-17166</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Marco, funny you ask since just a few weeks ago my old audio interface died so I was looking to try a new one. Based on reviews and recommendations and price, I got the Focusrite Scarlett 2i2...which I liked for its simplicity. It sounded pretty good for my four string fender basses, however, it just couldn&#039;t handle my active Fender Jazz V. I tried many variations of settings between the interface and my recording software (GarageBand) and just couldn&#039;t get the low B sounding right without compromising the overall sound, it would clip and distort way more than I found tolerable. There is probably a way I could have made it work, but I decided to simply try another highly recommended interface, the Audient iD14. So far it has been working wonderfully with my Jazz V, no clipping or anything and it sounds amazing. It&#039;s a bit more expensive than the Focusrite, but much cheaper than Apogee or Apollo. I hadn&#039;t considered it but you&#039;re probably right that perhaps the lack of a &quot;pad&quot; or &quot;soft limit&quot; is why I was having issues. ]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Marco, funny you ask since just a few weeks ago my old audio interface died so I was looking to try a new one. Based on reviews and recommendations and price, I got the Focusrite Scarlett 2i2&#8230;which I liked for its simplicity. It sounded pretty good for my four string fender basses, however, it just couldn&#8217;t handle my active Fender Jazz V. I tried many variations of settings between the interface and my recording software (GarageBand) and just couldn&#8217;t get the low B sounding right without compromising the overall sound, it would clip and distort way more than I found tolerable. There is probably a way I could have made it work, but I decided to simply try another highly recommended interface, the Audient iD14. So far it has been working wonderfully with my Jazz V, no clipping or anything and it sounds amazing. It&#8217;s a bit more expensive than the Focusrite, but much cheaper than Apogee or Apollo. I hadn&#8217;t considered it but you&#8217;re probably right that perhaps the lack of a &#8220;pad&#8221; or &#8220;soft limit&#8221; is why I was having issues. </p>
