	<item>
		<title>By: Duke</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/bass-tips/how-to-record-your-bass.html#comment-16426</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Duke]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 14 Sep 2015 02:02:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=11715#comment-16426</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[A couple of questions.
By &quot;thin&quot; do you mean bright or loss of volume?
If it&#039;s too bright (treble) try increasing the cap value.
For instance, if the existing cap is a .022 try increasing the value to.050 or more.
A big part of the reason early Fender P-basses sounded so &quot;dark&quot; or boomy was because of the 1.0 capacitors he used.
Many moons ago I found lowering them to .022 would make a P=Bass &quot;squawk&#039; like a Rickenbacker with the tone pot dimed.
Another trick is to change the pots from 250k to 500k.or vice versa depending on what you want to hear.
BTW:  Nice bass and good bio.  We share similar interests and influences.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>A couple of questions.<br />
By &#8220;thin&#8221; do you mean bright or loss of volume?<br />
If it&#8217;s too bright (treble) try increasing the cap value.<br />
For instance, if the existing cap is a .022 try increasing the value to.050 or more.<br />
A big part of the reason early Fender P-basses sounded so &#8220;dark&#8221; or boomy was because of the 1.0 capacitors he used.<br />
Many moons ago I found lowering them to .022 would make a P=Bass &#8220;squawk&#8217; like a Rickenbacker with the tone pot dimed.<br />
Another trick is to change the pots from 250k to 500k.or vice versa depending on what you want to hear.<br />
BTW:  Nice bass and good bio.  We share similar interests and influences.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
